Removal or Adjustment to our data

SC <- as.data.frame(read_excel("C:\\Users\\Ryan Thompson\\STAT-360-FINAL\\DAT_10 6 22.xlsx"))
data <- SC[,c(5:28)]

The first four dimensions of the data were dropped from our data frame. These values were county numbers, county names, state names, and a combination of county and state that did not necessitate inclusion. Our data possessed no categorical dimensions, and thus no use of dummy variables was necessary within the model. To account for the rows that were missing data values, we utilized a pairwise complete method to compute the correlation matrix and covariance matrix, which would then be utilized in our correlation plots, heatmaps, and future equations.

As this data is largely illegible at this scale, we’ve included our pairwise comparisons rendered in 4k along with this knit of both our original data, and our transformed data. Of our original data before any transformations, we see that the data are predominately weak and right skewed given their positive values, with most of the data appearing to be leptokurtic, possessing a value greater than 3. Some exceptions exist, wherein dimensions possess either strong positive or strong negtaive linear trends, which are highlighted within the pairwise comparison. Additional transformations may be performed as needed, but the majority of the data appear to fall well within acceptable parameters. Most notably however, the variables num_below_p50 and pop2018 have outrageously large values relative to everything else, and we will be performing transformations on them to attempt to bring them closer to being linear.

Applying Transformations

transformPop <- log(data[,2])
transformUnder50 <- log(data[,1])             
data <- data %>%
  mutate(pop2018 = log(pop2018))
colnames(data)[2] = "logPop2018"
data <- data %>%
  mutate(num_below_p50 = log(num_below_p50))
colnames(data)[1] = "logNum_Below_p50"

When looking at our pairs graph, we noticed that all of our variables were pretty linear (save some minimal heteroscedasticity) except for the first two variables, num_below_p50 and pop2018. These were our two population variables so it is understandable why these would be slightly more exponential due to the high amount of counties in the lower range of populations. We applied a log transform to both of these variables and found our pairs to look much more linear for the transformed variables. There is still a slight issue with the relationship between the transformed variables and the standard errors, but we believe that when we apply factor analysis and lump the standard errors in with the actual variables we won’t see this issue.

Visualizing and summarizing the covariability between each pair of dimensions

SIGMA <- cov(data, use = "pairwise.complete.obs")
R <- cor(data, use = "pairwise.complete.obs")
corrplot(R, method = "circle")

heatmap(R)

Our data initially yields a correlation matrix and a heat map that highlights several clusters that suggest a possible intrinsic dimensionality of potentially 7. Assessment of these values will be core to our project going forward to determine the factorization of the data. Naturally as a number of dimensions are the calculated standard error for their previous respective dimension, we note that these values are indeed highly correlated together intrinsically. That said, we must now check to determine whether any influential outliers exist in the data, and whether their removal presents a dramatic change to these plots overall.

Identifying our Outliers

CritVal = qchisq(p = 1-.05, df = 24)
covdata = cov(data, use = "pairwise.complete.obs")
Mal = matrix(ncol=24, nrow=24)
rownames(Mal) = colnames(data)
colnames(Mal) = colnames(data)
for(i in 1:24)
  {
  for(j in 1:24)
  {
    if( i!=j){
    Distances = mahalanobis(x=data[,c(i,j)], center = c(mean(data[,i]), mean(data[,j])), cov = cov(data[,c(i,j)],use = "pairwise.complete.obs"))
    Mal[i,j] = length(which(abs(Distances)>CritVal))
    }
  }}
sum(Mal[which(!is.na(Mal))]) / 2
## [1] 51

We see that we have 51 outliers. Our outliers are all found in the pairs of dimensions 21-24. Next We will change the values of these outliers to be NA.

Removing Outliers

OutliersRemoved = data
for(i in 21:24)
  {
  for(j in 21:24)
  {
    if( i!=j){
    Distances = mahalanobis(x=OutliersRemoved[,c(i,j)], center = c(mean(OutliersRemoved[,i]), mean(OutliersRemoved[,j])), cov = cov(OutliersRemoved[,c(i,j)],use = "pairwise.complete.obs"))
    OutliersRemoved[which(abs(Distances)>CritVal),i] = NA
    OutliersRemoved[which(abs(Distances)>CritVal),j] = NA
    }
  }}

We have now created a new dataset “OutliersRemoved” to allow us to compare the correlation plots with our outliers included and with them removed.

Ensuring there are no remaining Outliers

for(i in 1:24)
  {
  for(j in 1:24)
  {
    if( i!=j){
    Distances = mahalanobis(x=OutliersRemoved[,c(i,j)], center = c(mean(OutliersRemoved[,i]), mean(OutliersRemoved[,j])), cov = cov(OutliersRemoved[,c(i,j)],use = "pairwise.complete.obs"))
    Mal[i,j] = length(which(abs(Distances)>CritVal))
    }
  }}
sum(Mal[which(!is.na(Mal))]) / 2
## [1] 0

Thus we see we have successfully removed all of our outliers at a 5% significance level.

Reproducing Correlation Plots

CorData = cor(data, use = "pairwise.complete.obs")
AdjCor = cor(OutliersRemoved, use = "pairwise.complete.obs")
corrplot(CorData)

corrplot(AdjCor)

heatmap(CorData)

heatmap(AdjCor)

It does not appear that there is any major changes to our correlation when the outliers have been removed. We see a slight change in the factor grouping of the first three dimensions, but otherwise it doesn’t appear that our outliers have any real effect on the correlation of our dimensions.
